{"type":"message","id":"8c7d8231","parentId":"cf437153","timestamp":"2026-03-24T20:17:31.489Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_t1a512gx1lwz_2","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"# Pulse: 2026-03-24 161543\n\n## Applied Mutations\nNo mutations applied this cycle.\n\n\n## LLM Response\n<think>\r\nLet me analyze the current state and determine the best single action to advance the goals.\r\n\r\nCurrent situation:\r\n- Phase 1 IN PROGRESS: Compression primitives - CFI analysis complete, next is conditional content analysis\r\n- The core breakthrough has been documented: CFI ≠ Causal Discovery\r\n- The immediate next experiment is \"Conditional Content Analysis\" - testing whether moderate-frequency tokens (freq=60-80%) actually cause different research content in the next pulse\r\n\r\nThe conditional content analysis is the highest priority next step. It will help distinguish Pattern Information from Causal Information empirically.\r\n\r\nLet me design this experiment:\r\n1. Pick tokens with moderate frequency (e.g., freq=60-80% range, so freq 120-160 in a 200-pulse corpus)\r\n2. Split pulse pairs into groups where T is present vs absent in pulse N\r\n3. Compare the research content/metrics of pulse N+1 between the two groups\r\n4. If no difference: tokens are just scaffolding (predictive but not causal)\r\n5. If yes: tokens are genuinely causal\r\n\r\nCandidates mentioned:\r\n- \"compression\" (freq=199, CFI=0.995) - too high\r\n- \"causal\" (freq=162, CFI=0.981) - freq 162 is in range\r\n- \"phase\" (freq=187, CFI=0.946) - still high\r\n\r\nActually looking at the frequency distribution, most tokens are either:\r\n- Very high frequency (180-200) - constant format, metaprogramming\r\n- Low frequency (<50) - rare content\r\n\r\nThe sweet spot for conditional analysis would be tokens with freq in the 60-120 range (if any exist in this corpus).\r\n\r\nLet me check what the hybrid scoring analysis found - it mentioned \"Tokens with freq=200, CFI=1.00\" are constant. The goal is to find tokens where freq < 120.\r\n\r\nThe experiment design document should:\r\n1. \r\n\r\nDefine the hypothesis clearly\r\n2. Select the right token set\r\n3. Detail the methodology for comparing pulse pairs\r\n4. Establish concrete pass/fail criteria\r\n5. Set a reasonable timeline for execution\r\n\r\nI should create a research document that outlines this experiment rather than modifying existing code, since this is fundamentally a research planning task.\r\n</think>\r\n\r\n### OBSERVATION\r\nThe core breakthrough establishes that CFI measures Pattern Information (Layer 1 compression) while Causal Discovery needs Transfer Entropy (Layer 2). The next critical experiment is Conditional Content Analysis to empirically distinguish scaffolding from genuine causation for moderate-frequency tokens.\r\n\r\n### ACTION\r\nCreate the experiment design document for Conditional Content Analysis - the highest priority pending task that will empirically test whether tokens like \"causal\" (freq=162) are genuinely causal or just predictive scaffolding.\r\n\r\n### MUTATION\r\n```\r\nold_text: (new file)\r\nnew_text: # Conditional Content Analysis Experiment\r\n\r\n**Status:** Ready to execute  \r\n**Priority:** 🔴 Highest  \r\n**Corpus:** 200 pulses (pulse_2026-03-*.md)\r\n\r\n## Objective\r\n\r\nEmpirically distinguish **Pattern Information** (CFI) from **Causal Information** for moderate-frequency tokens.\r\n\r\n**Hypothesis:**\r\n- If T-present vs T-absent groups show NO difference in next-pulse content → T is scaffolding (predictive but causally inert)\r\n- If groups show SIGNIFICANT difference → T is genuinely causal\r\n\r\n## Token Selection\r\n\r\nNeed tokens in the \"gray zone\" where freq is neither constant-format (180-200) nor rare (<20):\r\n\r\n| Token | Freq | CFI | Status |\r\n|-------|------|-----|--------|\r\n| causal | 162 | 0.981 | CANDIDATE - mid-range |\r\n| phase | 187 | 0.946 | Too high (constant format) |\r\n| compression | 199 | 0.995 | Too high (metaprogramming) |\r\n| transfer | ~45 | ~0.8 | Could be candidate |\r\n\r\n**Primary target:** \"causal\" (freq=162, CFI=0.981)\r\n\r\n## Methodology\r\n\r\n1. **Group pulses by token presence:**\r\n   - Group A: pulses where T appears in text\r\n   - Group B: pulses where T does NOT appear\r\n\r\n2. **Compare next-pulse metrics between groups:**\r\n   - Semantic similarity (embedding cosine)\r\n   - Research advancement (new doc references, strategy changes)\r\n   - Token overlap (Jaccard)\r\n\r\n3. **Statistical test:**\r\n   - Compare Group A next-pulse vs Group B next-pulse distributions\r\n   - T-test or KS-test on similarity scores\r\n\r\n## Success Criteria\r\n\r\n| Result | Interpretation |\r\n|--------|-----------------|\r\n| Δsimilarity < 0.05 | T is scaffolding (CFI sufficient, no causal effect) |\r\n| Δsimilarity ≥ 0.15 | T is causally relevant (need Transfer Entropy) |\r\n| Ambiguous | Need more pulses or different token selection |\r\n\r\n## Expected Outcome\r\n\r\nGiven that \"causal\" appears 162/200 times (81%), most pulses are in Group A. This creates imbalanced groups but still provides statistical power.\r\n\r\n**If \"causal\" tokens are scaffolding:** Their presence predicts nothing about future research trajectory.\r\n\r\n**If \"causal\" tokens are causal:** Removing them would measurably alter the research arc.\r\n\r\n## Execution Plan\r\n\r\n```bash\r\n# Extract all pulse text\r\nls pulses/pulse_2026-03-*.md | wc -l  # Should be ~200\r\n\r\n# For each candidate token T:\r\n# 1. Find pulses containing T\r\n# 2. For each T-present pulse, get its next-pulse\r\n# 3. For each T-absent pulse, get its next-pulse\r\n# 4. Compare content similarity\r\n```\r\n\r\n## Document Output\r\n\r\nResults will go in: `research/CONDITIONAL-CONTENT-R\n\n## For Next Instantiation\n- Proposed mutations waiting: 1\n- Completed at: 2026-03-24 16:16:06\r\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1774383451487}}
